summary.name: unemployment-across-industries
summary.dataset_description: A dataset containing information about unemployment rates across various industries from 2000 to 2010.

properties.description: The industry sector to which the unemployment data belongs.

goals.question: What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate over time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify if there is an overall increase or decrease in unemployment rate across all industries over the years.

goals.question: Which industry had the highest unemployment rate in a given year?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of unemployment rate by industry for a specific year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify which industry had the highest unemployment rate in a given year and compare it with other industries.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment count across all industries?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of unemployment count across all industries and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the average unemployment rate for each industry?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of average unemployment rate by industry
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us compare the average unemployment rate across different industries and identify which industries have higher or lower unemployment rates.

goals.question: What is the correlation between unemployment count and unemployment rate?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of unemployment count vs unemployment rate
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify if there is a correlation between unemployment count and unemployment rate and how strong the correlation is.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    for industry in data['series'].unique():
        industry_data = data[data['series'] == industry]
        ax.plot(industry_data['date'], industry_data['rate'], label=industry)
    
    ax.set_title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?')
    ax.set_xlabel('Year')
    ax.set_ylabel('Unemployment Rate (%)')
    ax.legend(loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Filter data for a specific year
    year = 2008  # Replace with the desired year
    data = data[data['year'] == year]

    # Group by industry and calculate the mean unemployment rate
    data_grouped = data.groupby('series')['rate'].mean().reset_index()

    # Sort by unemployment rate
    data_grouped = data_grouped.sort_values('rate', ascending=False)

    # Create a bar chart
    plt.bar(data_grouped['series'], data_grouped['rate'], color='b')
    plt.title('Which industry had the highest unemployment rate in a given year?')
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate (%)')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.legend([f'Highest: {data_grouped.iloc[0]["series"]} ({data_grouped.iloc[0]["rate"]:.2f}%)'])

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.hist(data['count'], bins=20, color='blue', alpha=0.7, label='Unemployment Count')
    plt.axvline(data['count'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median: {data['count'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Unemployment Count')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment count across all industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    avg_unemployment_rate = data.groupby('series')['rate'].mean()
    industries = avg_unemployment_rate.index
    
    plt.bar(industries, avg_unemployment_rate)
    plt.title('What is the average unemployment rate for each industry?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Average Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(["Average Unemployment Rate"])
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.scatter(data['count'], data['rate'], c=data['series'].astype('category').cat.codes, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.5)
    plt.xlabel('Unemployment Count')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between unemployment count and unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    
    legend_elements = [plt.Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', label=series, markerfacecolor=c, markersize=10) for series, c in zip(data['series'].unique(), plt.get_cmap('viridis').colors[:len(data['series'].unique())])]
    plt.legend(handles=legend_elements, title='Industry Sectors', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0.)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
